The spin-adduct decay is affected by the environment, such as the concentration of the spin trap (Roubaud et al., 1997). To find out the actual amount of trapped ROS upon illumination, we need to also study the decay process of spin-adducts in the absence of light, which was not performed in this study. Furthermore, spin trapping is not the only reaction that ROS undergoes. There are many other chemical reactions that the highly reactive free radicals easily participate in to form EPR silent products (XR). This in turn influences the spin-trapping efficiency (E), which can be described as the ratio of the spin-adduct formation rate to the rate of all other reactions (Vi) and free radical formation (13).12R∙+X→XR\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
